    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** - June 1, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 💻 Nvidia wants the PC back\n\nNvidia used Computex to pitch the laptop as a local agent box, because apparently cloud bills needed a smaller accomplice.\n\n- **The chip:** Reuters says RTX Spark, co-developed with MediaTek, is built to run AI agents on laptops and desktops instead of only in the cloud.\n- **The partner:** Microsoft's Surface Laptop Ultra is the first RTX Spark Surface, with a Blackwell RTX GPU, up to 128GB of unified memory and CUDA support, due this fall.\n- **The flank:** Vera CPU early users include OpenAI, Anthropic and SpaceX; Nvidia pitches 1.8x faster AI task completion versus x86.\n\n*The app-centric PC is being politely replaced by a machine that opens the apps itself.*\n\n**Sources:** [Reuters](https://ca.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/nvidia-launches-new-chip-to-bring-ai-directly-to-personal-computers-4667868) | [Nvidia](https://investor.nvidia.com/news/press-release-details/2026/NVIDIA-Unveils-Vera-the-CPU-for-Agents/default.aspx) | [Windows Central](https://www.windowscentral.com/hardware/surface/microsoft-surface-laptop-ultra-announced-computex-2026)\n\n---\n\n## 🤖 Nvidia gives labs a humanoid starter kit\n\nPhysical AI's bottleneck is no longer just data; it is also everyone rebuilding the same robot stack with grant money and optimism.\n\n- **The body:** Nvidia's Isaac GR00T reference robot combines a Unitree H2 Plus, Sharpa tactile hands and Jetson AGX Thor T5000 with 128GB of memory and 2,070 FP4 teraflops.\n- **The bench:** Ai2, ETH Zurich, Stanford Robotics Center and UC San Diego will use the design; availability through Unitree is planned for late 2026.\n- **The brain:** Cosmos 3 is an open world model for robots and autonomous systems to reason, generate action data and predict environments.\n\n*Robotics now has a reference design, which means the standards fight can begin properly.*\n\n**Sources:** [Nvidia](https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2026/06/01/3303990/0/en/NVIDIA-Announces-NVIDIA-Isaac-GR00T-Reference-Humanoid-Robot-for-Academic-Research.html) | [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/06/01/nvidia-ai-push-cosmos-3-world-model)\n\n---\n\n## 🧑‍💻 MiniMax undercuts the coding club\n\nThe model race has reached the fun phase where a Chinese lab says near-frontier coding should cost less than the coffee spilled during the benchmark run.\n\n- **The model:** MiniMax launched M3 with a 1M-token context window, native multimodality and agentic coding support, calling it the first open-weight model to combine all three.\n- **The scoreboard:** MiniMax claims 59.0% on SWE-Bench Pro, ahead of GPT-5.5 and Gemini 3.1 Pro and close to Claude Opus 4.7.\n- **The plumbing:** Its sparse-attention design cuts per-token compute at 1M context to 1/20 of the previous model, with 9x faster prefill and 15x faster decoding.\n\n*Frontier envy now ships with a discount aisle and a very long context window.*\n\n**Sources:** [MiniMax](https://www.minimax.io/blog/minimax-m3) | [Techmeme](https://www.techmeme.com/river)\n\n---\n\n## 🛡️ Anthropic loans Europe the bug cannon\n\nCybersecurity regulation has found a new ritual: ask nicely for access to the model that finds the holes before everyone else gets one.\n\n- **The access:** Bloomberg Law reports Anthropic will let ENISA join Project Glasswing and test Claude Mythos Preview before a broader rollout.\n- **The receipts:** Anthropic's disclosure dashboard already lists findings across wolfSSL, CraftCMS and FreeRDP, including high-severity crypto and memory bugs.\n- **The policy mess:** Mythos turns vulnerability discovery into an arms race where disclosure windows, patch queues and model access all become governance problems.\n\n*The good news: the bugs are easier to find. The bad news: that sentence has two endings.*\n\n**Sources:** [Bloomberg Law](https://news.bloomberglaw.com/artificial-intelligence/anthropic-to-give-eus-cybersecurity-agency-access-to-mythos) | [Anthropic](https://red.anthropic.com/2026/cvd/)\n\n---\n\n## 🏭 France orders an AI power socket\n\nEurope's AI sovereignty plan has reached the honest part: a data center so large the strategy can be measured in megawatts.\n\n- **The campus:** Ardian and Verne plan an AI infrastructure site in Ile-de-France with up to €5 billion of investment and a 500MW target capacity.\n- **The timeline:** Data Center Dynamics says the initial phase is expected to exceed 200MW by 2030.\n- **The bid:** The project is designed to support the AION consortium's French proposal under the EU AI Gigafactories initiative.\n\n*Sovereign AI, it turns out, is partly a model policy and partly a very expensive extension cord.*\n\n**Sources:** [Data Center Dynamics](https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/ardian-verne-target-500mw-data-center-campus-in-france/) | [Techmeme](https://www.techmeme.com/river)"
  }
]
